06239nam a22008295i 9780271090672DE-B159720230328044521.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230328t20122012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710906727 a10.1515/97802710906722doi  a(DE-B1597)586186  a(OCoLC)1262308289  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX1905b.E63 2012 7aREL0330002bisacsh04a262/.122422300aEarly Modern Studies. Episcopal Reform and Politics in Early Modern Europe /ced. by Jennifer Mara DeSilva. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly Modern Studies ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword: The Local Nature of Episcopal Reform in the Age of the Council of Trent -- tIntroduction: A Living Example -- tPart 1: Episcopal Authority -- tHierarchy that Had Fought: Episcopal Promotion during the Reign of Mary I (1553–58) and the Roots of Episcopal Resistance to the Elizabethan Religious Settlement -- tBishops in the Habsburg Netherlands on the Eve of the Catholic Renewal, 1515–59 -- tOffice and Patronage in Mid-Sixteenth-Century Tortona -- tPart 2: Pastoral Practice -- tThe Absentee Bishop in Residence: Paris de’ Grassi, Bishop of Pesaro, 1513–28 -- tPapal Authority, Episcopal Reservation, and Abortion in Sixteenth-Century Italy -- tMinistering to Catholics and Protestants Alike: The Preaching, Polemics, and Pastoral Care of François de Sales -- tPart 3: Clerical Reform -- tGender, Resistance, and the Limits of Episcopal Authority: Sébastien Zamet’s Relationships with Nuns, 1615–55 -- tChallenges to Episcopal Authority in Seventeenth-Century Padua -- tTrials That Should Have Been: The Question of Judicial Jurisdiction over French Bishops in the Seventeenth Century and the Self-Narration of the Roman Inquisition -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the tumultuous period of the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries when ecclesiastical reform spread across Europe, the traditional role of the bishop as a public exemplar of piety, morality, and communal administration came under attack. In communities where there was tension between religious groups or between spiritual and secular governing bodies, the bishop became a lightning rod for struggles over hierarchical authority and institutional autonomy. These struggles were intensified by the ongoing negotiation of the episcopal role and by increased criticism of the cleric, especially during periods of religious war and in areas that embraced reformed churches. This volume contextualizes the diversity of episcopal experience across early modern Europe, while showing the similarity of goals and challenges among various confessional, social, and geographical communities. Until now there have been few studies that examine the spectrum of responses to contemporary challenges, the high expectations, and the continuing pressure bishops faced in their public role as living examples of Christian ideals.Contributors include: William V. Hudon, Jennifer Mara DeSilva, Raymond A. Powell, Hans Cools, Antonella Perin, John Alexander, John Christopoulos, Jill Fehleison, Linda Lierheimer, Celeste McNamara, Jean-Pascal Gay  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2023) 0aChristianity and politicsxCatholic ChurchxHistory. 0aChristianity and politicszEuropexHistory. 0aClergyxOfficexHistory. 0aEpiscopacyxHistory. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChristopoulos, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCools, Hans, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re